content.description: This aesthetic route brings a bit of everything from finger cracks & techy movements off the deck to powerful throws & a heart breaker crux at the top! Have fun, this climb is worth it!
content.location: Scramble up a dirty corner to reach the belay.  The climb goes up the distinct 1st left-facing corner through the black then green rock.

content.description: A boulder problem immediately after the first bolt guards easy but pleasant climbing up top. Cool holds on excellent rock, however it's over far too quickly to be considered a classic.

Start out by scrambling easily up the low angle ramp to gain the first bolt.  Pick your way up crimps on the face until the holds disappear just shy of the shallow left facing dihedral.  Once you gain the dihedral, the climbing eases up some, but the bolts are spaced enough to make your think twice about falling.  After pulling the final roof, finish on dirty (sometimes wet) jugs to reach the chains.
content.protection: Quickdraws...8 is probably enough, 10 is definitely enough.
content.location: Starts on the low angle ramp just right of Deadwood.

content.description: This route has it all. Everything from wee-baby crimps to problem child chicken heads . Good technical climbing up a temporarily dirty face. This will clean up quite well with more traffic. The grade is an estimate, it felt slightly harder than Country Cowboy, and better holds keep unearthing themselves as the route cleans up.
content.location: 1 route left of the black streak route Matt Dennis, and two routes left of Country Cowboy.

content.description:
One move wonder down low off crimps leads to easier terrain on jug above. 

  Attentive belay necessary for the first 2 bolts.
content.location: Left most route located on wood wall. First one you see as you walk in.

content.description: All those years of listening to true crime podcasts is about to pay off when you harness your inner-detective skills in order to discover the correct holds required to make it up the perpetually chalk-free black streak.
content.location: This route is located in the black streak left of Country Cowboy.  The two routes share the first bolt.

content.description:
Easy face climbing down low rides you up to a small roof where a powerful shoulder move resides.    From here keep it together for the easy but sustained finish.  

  Tough for the grade.

Tough low crux into a blunt arete finish. 

  Tough for the grade.

Great moderate at the creek! 

  Stickclip the first bolt and do a small but easy boulder problem to a good ledge. From here fire up small sequences that end on good ledges until you reach the base of a small roof. 

  Find the good holds and pull over the roof to a glory jug finish. 

  Awesome moves on this route.
content.location: Located to the right of "Morning Wood"

content.description: Start on a flake and cruise jugs to the top.
content.protection: 6 bolts to 2 fixed stainless steel biners on the anchors.
content.location: This is the second from the farthest right route (Reverse Cowgirl is farthest) on the Wood Wall. Shares the first bolt with Matt Dennis then breaks right and follows the line of bolts to the right of the black streak.

content.description: Some like this route better than Pet the Moose...and others don't. Start the same as PTM but venture out right after the lower crux sequences of PTM and drift right into and independent line. Several ways to do the upper crux. Pick your poison crimp or dyno/deadpoint (dyno is way cooler). Originally started by Andrew Blann and later finished by Kyle Rowden.
content.location: Same start as Pet the Moose then branch out right around the 4th or 5th bolt.

content.description:
Smooth wall with large bulges and cool holds. 

  Hosts quality 5.11's and 12a's
